This is the Ruy Lopez. I don't encounter it too much, but I hear that it is a great opening. My lag of experience for very complex openings prevents me from using it. However, I counterattack this opening with moderate ease.
Correct me if I'm wrong, but I believe from my experience that this is the Berlin Defence.
This is not part of the opening played, therefore, it is an inaccurate move. 4.O-O is the main line and 4.d3 is the Mortimer variation while 4.d4 is the Nyholm Attack.

When calculating analysis, I was informed by a grandmaster that Bishop pairs are worth a lot (even more so in the middle game). I am shocked that my opponent didn't realize how useless he has been treating his Bishops.
I knew that White's Queen was in a pathetic place, so I take advantage of it.
When White grabbed one pawn too many, the equal game turned into a Knightmare for White. I knew he would regret losing Bishops, because White only has Knights and Rooks to rely on.
Here comes my once forgotten Bishop who sacrifices herself for the Queen. This opens way for her sibling, the DSB, to carry out the next assault.
Another severe blunder by White, who is now almost entirely destroyed. 12.dxe4 Bxe5 13.c3 should have been played.
After going down 11 points, White is forced to defend to the bitter end.
